  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering is a serious criminal offense with significant penalties. Here are some key details:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Imprisonment of up to 20 years\n- Substantial financial fines\n- Potential forfeiture of assets involved in the transaction\n\n2. Specific Statutory Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 covers money laundering criminal offenses\n- Penalties vary based on specific circumstances and intent\n\n3. Potential Additional Consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Civil penalties\n- Asset seizure\n\n4. Factors Influencing Sentencing:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Specific nature of the criminal activity\n- Prior criminal history\n- Level of involvement in the offense\n\n5. Monetary Penalties:\n- Fines can be up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n\nThe exact penalties depend on specific case details and prosecutorial discretion. For precise legal advice about a specific situation, consulting a qualified criminal defense attorney is recommended.",
